Here’s how to make #scotcheroos, a Midwest favorite!

Ingredients: 
6 cups: Rice Krispies 
1 cup each of the following: sugar, light corn syrup, creamy peanut butter, semi-sweet chocolate chips and butterscotch chips

You can find all of these ingredients at @FleetFarmOfficial.

In a large saucepan, you’re going to heat the sugar and corn syrup until the sugar dissolves. Do not boil it. 

Then you’re going to mix in the peanut butter and stir in the Rice Krispies. Spread the mixture evenly into a greased 9x13 pan. 

For the topping, heat up the chocolate and butterscotch chips in 20 to 30 second increments… stirring in between… until it’s smooth. Spread the mix over the top. 

Let the bars set, or speed it up by putting them in the fridge for 5 minutes before eating. Enjoy!

Wondering where to visit in Wisconsin? 🧀🍺 Here are a few recommendations! And some more thoughts…

- If you’re into winter sports, winter IS a good time to visit. I’m just in love with summer & fall ;)

- Milwaukee is also known as the city of festivals. Checking out the largest music festival in the world, Summerfest, is a fun bucket list event. 

What else did I miss?! 👇

ONE year ago Joe and I said “I Do” in downtown Milwaukee! 🎉 Here are a few things we loved about our wedding… 
1) We kept it small. Only people who were a regular part of our lives and relationship were there to celebrate with us… immediate family and best friends. Bonus: this really kept the costs down! 
2) We kept it all under one roof. I highly recommend our venue, The Lookout at Kinn Guesthouse. Their rooftop venue with a terrace has gorgeous views of downtown Milwaukee. And the best part is our guests and we were only an elevator ride away from our overnight stay in their chic hotel rooms.
3) We DJ’d our own wedding. Disclaimer: this might not work for a bigger wedding. But it was perfect for our size group (30 people). Joe and I are BIG music people. So we made two Spotify playlists with our favorite music… 1. for cocktail hour/dinner and 2. for dancing. It was so special to hear meaningful songs throughout the evening! 
4) Old fashioneds for cocktail hour (no explanation needed 😉)

Swipe to the last slide to watch our wedding video for more things we loved! ❤️

Brandied cherries recipe for old fashioneds 🍒🥃👇 (hit save to find it later) 

Ingredients:
Brandy 
Cherries 
Sugar 

Tools:
Cherry pitter 
Bowl to catch cherries 
Canning jars 

Instructions:
Remove cherry stems and pits
Fill your jar with cherries leaving a little space 
Add 1/3 sugar and 2/3 brandy (portions are forgiving, feel free to do less booze) 
Seal the can and shake it 
Store in fridge or dark cool spot for at least 24 hours and up to months! 

Give as a gift or add to your old fashioneds. 😋 🥃 

Simple right? Enjoy! 🍒 

#oldfashionedcocktail #cocktailrecipes #wisconsin

How to make brandy slush (a Midwest classic)🍹👇

Shout out to my friends at @midwestmunchers for this recipe!

Ingredients:
7 cups water
2 cups sugar
6 black tea bags
12 oz. orange juice concentrate (thawed)
12 oz. lemonade concentrate (thawed)
2-4 cups brandy
Lemon-lime soda
Lime & orange slice (for garnish)

Instructions:
First, make sure you have an empty ice cream bucket ready to go! 
Then, boil the water and sugar 
Whisk until the sugar dissolves
Remove from the heat and add the black tea bags 
Steep for about 5 minutes
Throw away the tea bags
Transfer mixture to ice cream bucket
Add thawed orange juice and lemonade concentrate
Add brandy
Mix, cover with a lid and freeze
Fill your glass about ¾ of the way, top it off with some lemon-lime soda and garnish

Save this recipe for your next holiday party 😋 Cheers!
